HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 1264
By Chism
A RESOLUTION to continue honoring the memory of Reverend
Jesse L. Jackson, Sr.
WHEREAS, one month has passed since the members of this General Assembly
mourned the loss of Reverend Jesse L. Jackson, Sr., and we continue to reflect upon his
extraordinary life and enduring legacy; and
WHEREAS, Reverend Jackson's lifelong commitment to civil rights, voting rights, and
human dignity remains deeply embedded in the conscience of this nation and continues to
guide the work of leaders and communities alike; and
WHEREAS, even in his absence, the impact of his leadership through the Rainbow
PUSH Coalition and his tireless advocacy for justice, equality, and opportunity continues to be
felt across Tennessee, the United States, and the world; and
WHEREAS, Reverend Jackson's voice, which called upon all people to "Keep hope
alive," still resonates as a moral compass for those striving to build a more just and equitable
society; and
WHEREAS, this General Assembly recognizes that the passage of time does not
diminish the significance of his contributions but instead deepens our appreciation for the
foundation he laid for future generations; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that we pause once more to honor his memory, reaffirm his
ideals, and recommit ourselves to the principles for which he so courageously stood; now,
therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
HJR1264
016664
- 1 -

CONCURRING, that we continue to honor and remember Reverend Jesse L. Jackson, Sr., one
month after his passing, reflecting upon his enduring legacy of hope, justice, and service.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we renew our deepest sympathy and continued
condolences to the family of Reverend Jackson as they carry forward his remarkable legacy.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
